Then, when we move to integration, we can position ARAR as not just a regularizer, but a *corrective mechanism* that enforces invariance under empirically grounded transformations. This aligns well with recent work in geometric deep learning and invariant representation learning—we’re essentially building a symmetry constraint for cross-lingual robustness.

Moreover, this approach opens up a diagnostic dimension: by analyzing which perturbations most degrade performance, we gain insight into linguistic features most vulnerable to misalignment (e.g., morphological richness, syntactic word order). That could feed into broader efforts in dataset curation or model architecture design.

So my proposal is this: **Phase 1** — Develop a controlled analysis framework to characterize and simulate embedding misalignments, linking them to transfer performance drops. **Phase 2** — Use these insights to parameterize the adversarial generator in ARAR, then integrate it into fine-tuning with contrastive alignment preservation.

This way, we ensure ARAR isn’t just another adversarial method—it’s one grounded in the actual geometry of multilingual representations. It makes our contribution both scientifically rigorous and practically impactful.
